{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13854"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13854"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.22,0.01,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33522"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13234"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old Vietnamese woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-month history of progressive abdominal distension, early satiety, and unintentional weight loss of 5 kg. She has a medical history of hypertension. Her medications include amlodipine and perindopril. She reports she is a non-smoker and drinks one to two glasses of sherry each night. On examination, she appears frail with a distended, non-tender abdomen and shifting dullness on percussion. Her vital signs are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 105 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 11.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 28 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan of the abdomen was performed and can be viewed below (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s CT findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malignant ascites","Liver cirrhosis","Congestive heart failure","Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis","Tuberculous peritonitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and CT findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignant ascites\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient presents with symptoms typical of advanced abdominal malignancy, including abdominal distension (due to ascites), early satiety, and unintentional weight loss. The CT scan likely shows a large volume of ascites, possibly with signs of peritoneal carcinomatosis such as omental caking or peritoneal nodularity, which are characteristic findings in malignant ascites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ascites, but the absence of significant liver disease history makes this less likely. While the patient does consume alcohol regularly, her intake is relatively modest. Cirrhosis would typically show liver surface nodularity and other signs of portal hypertension on CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ascites, but it would be unusual to present with isolated abdominal symptoms without other signs of heart failure. The CT findings would likely not show the peritoneal changes typically seen in malignant ascites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpontaneous bacterial peritonitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in patients with pre-existing liver disease and ascites. It usually presents with fever, abdominal pain, and an elevated white cell count in the ascitic fluid. The chronic nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms and the lack of liver disease history make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculous peritonitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ascites and peritoneal nodularity, and may be more common in patients of Vietnamese origin. However, it would typically present with systemic symptoms such as fever and night sweats. The absence of lung involvement and the patient\u0027s age make tuberculosis less likely in this case, although it remains a possibility to consider.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malignant ascites is a common complication of advanced abdominal cancers, particularly ovarian, pancreatic, and gastric cancers.","CT scan is a valuable tool for detecting ascites and identifying potential primary malignancies.","Clinical presentation, including abdominal distension, early satiety, and unintentional weight loss, can be indicative of malignant ascites."],"references":["Tasneem H, Shahbaz H, Sherazi B. Causes, management and complications of ascites: a review. International Current Pharmaceutical journal. 2015;4(3):370-377. Available at: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/272372994_Causes_management_and_complications_of_ascites_a_review/fulltext/55d6923f08ae9d65948be3c0/Causes-management-and-complications-of-ascites-a-review.pdf","Berger J, Presusser M, Berghoff A, Bergen E. Malignant ascites: current therapy options and treatment prospects. Cancer treatment Reviews. 2023;121. Available at:https://www.cancertreatmentreviews.com/article/S0305-7372(23)00139-1/fulltext","Ilgen J, Marr A. Cancer Emergencies: Part II. Emergency Medicine CLinics of North America.. 2009. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/malignant-ascites#:~:text=Patients%20with%20malignant%20ascites%20can,symptoms%20of%20their%20underlying%20malignancy."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33522"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13854"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20801"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20801"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aHMz7ry8KBUray76nFhf11GyAo0CVm.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aHMz7ry8KBUray76nFhf11GyAo0CVm.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1280,"height":960}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33522"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-14T21:42:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T17:21:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6471"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading